platformd-secretd NEWS
======================

platformd-secretd 0.1.2

  Audit hardening:

  * The trust gate now guards protected mutation, not only release: SetSecret,
    SetAttributes, Delete and a replace-on-CreateItem of an item carrying a
    platformd.* attribute require that item's policy to be satisfied. This closes
    a downgrade where a caller could strip an item's policy with SetAttributes
    and then read it freely. Deleting a collection is refused if it would destroy
    a gated item whose policy is unsatisfied.
  * The interactive step-up is asynchronous: a stale fresh-verification or
    trusted-platform read defers its D-Bus reply and drives the polkit prompt /
    platformd-verifyd call on the event loop, so a slow reader never freezes the
    daemon for other clients.
  * An encrypted store that cannot be opened (no key, wrong key, or a newer /
    foreign on-disk version) disables writes instead of overwriting it with an
    empty store — one misconfigured boot no longer destroys the secrets. The unit
    STATUS reflects encrypted / plaintext / read-only.
  * logind lock tracking rebinds when the session changes (log out / in), rather
    than binding once at startup and going deaf.

platformd-secretd 0.1.1

  * Trusted-platform items step up through platformd-verifyd: a stale
    platformd.policy=trusted-platform read re-verifies presence (fingerprint,
    face, …) and refreshes platformd-trustd, releasing only if the platform is
    then trusted. Documentation brought in line with the platformd-trustd gate.

platformd-secretd 0.1.0

  First working release of the platform-authentication-aware Secret Service
  provider for org.freedesktop.secrets.

  Features:
    * Full freedesktop.org Secret Service API over D-Bus: Service, Collections
      (the default served at both the collection and alias paths, plus
      CreateCollection / Delete for additional named collections), Items,
      Sessions and Prompts; libsecret / secret-tool compatible. Change signals
      (CollectionCreated / CollectionDeleted, ItemCreated / ItemChanged /
      ItemDeleted) and writable Label / Attributes.
    * Encrypted session transport: the Diffie-Hellman key-agreement algorithm
      (dh-ietf1024-sha256-aes128-cbc-pkcs7), byte-compatible with libsecret, so
      secret values are encrypted in transit and never cross the bus in the
      clear. Plain transport is still offered for clients that ask for it.
    * Encryption at rest: AES-256-GCM with an Argon2id-derivable key, the key
      delivered as a systemd credential ($CREDENTIALS_DIRECTORY/vault-key). With
      no key configured the store is kept in the clear (for already-encrypted
      homes, e.g. systemd-homed luks/fscrypt). The daemon detects the homed
      storage backend and warns when secrets would sit in the clear on an
      unencrypted home.
    * The trust gate:
        - lock state tracks the desktop session via systemd-logind: locking the
          screen locks the secrets, unlocking restores them. While the session is
          locked, Unlock is refused -- the only key is unlocking the session
          itself, which takes real authentication. An explicit Service.Lock is
          cleared through a Prompt object that re-authenticates via polkit;
        - caller identity is graded from D-Bus peer credentials
          (unknown / same-user-weak / systemd-unit / sandboxed-app);
        - items may opt into fresh-verification and a minimum caller grade via the
          "platformd.policy" and "platformd.min-grade" attributes; a stale
          fresh-verification item triggers an interactive polkit prompt
          (auth_self, action io.platformd.secret1.verify-fresh) for on-demand
          re-verification.
    * secretctl(1): status, list, lock, unlock.
    * A Varlink admin/introspection interface, io.platformd.Secret (GetStatus,
      ListItems -- metadata only, never secrets), the way systemd's own services
      expose one; browse it with varlinkctl. Served on
      $XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/platformd-secretd/io.platformd.Secret.
    * Structured audit logging to the journal
      (journalctl PLATFORMD_EVENT=secret-read).
    * Memory hygiene: secrets zeroized on free, vault key mlocked,
      MemorySwapMax=0, LimitCORE=0, and systemd sandboxing on the unit.

  Tests (meson test): vault (crypto primitives), integration (isolated D-Bus
  store/lookup round-trip), and malformed-store (parser robustness against
  truncated / bit-flipped / hostile store files). Green under ASan/UBSan.

  Versioning: the 0.x series is pre-release. The 1.0 tag is gated on an
  independent security review.
